His agrarian perspective heavily influenced his views on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and the judicial system. He was passionate about preserving and promoting agriculture, which he deemed superior among all professions.

John believed the United States held a unique opportunity to establish a flawless government, as it lacked native traditions that might hinder such a system. He strongly upheld the natural rights of man, emphasizing their interdependence; denying any one right would diminish all others. These rights, he argued, should be protected from government interference. He viewed the "state of nature" as a place where the strong and cunning prospered, but in civilization, this dynamic should be moderated.

To achieve this ideal society, Taylor envisioned a government that acknowledged both the good and evil in human nature. He was steadfast in his dualistic morality, asserting that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He deemed good principles as those that safeguard private property, enhance agriculture, and discourage capitalism. A government founded on such principles would function equitably, despite inevitable human self-interest. Self-interest, he maintained, was natural but harmful when it led to sub-societal exploitation. A robust government was necessary to control this innate evil, but it too required oversight to prevent the introduction of corrupt principles.

Taylor, like many contemporaries, called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He advocated for a minimal Federal government with no powers beyond those explicitly stated, recognizing that an expansive Federal system could become tyrannical. However, he also warned that a literal, unreflective interpretation could degenerate into corruption. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly defined the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was quite disheartening, and the reason for it is unclear. The onset of winter in a New England campus could be one factor, as fewer people commute by bicycle or on foot. Additionally, December marks the end of the fall semester, with everyone busy with final schoolwork and grading, causing the commuter log to be overlooked. The holiday season also brings a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January, which might also explain the low submissions for that month. However, February's low numbers are puzzling. It's possible that projects like this initially attract a burst of enthusiasm, which then naturally fades. To combat this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which successfully increased log submissions for that month. One challenge we faced was maintaining project momentum in the face of natural engagement decline, holiday breaks, and semester holidays. Another challenge is that people deeply value the freedom and independence of driving their cars, making it crucial to offer incentives for alternative commuting. We provided gift certificates to local businesses as prizes, but it would have been interesting to see if larger prizes like bicycles, hybrid cars, or electric cars could have boosted participation. The value of the prizes didn't change during the project, but increasing their value over time, such as announcing a couple of bicycles in December, a hybrid car in January, might have increased engagement instead of decreasing it.

Every day, when I return to my Taipei home, I am greeted by Soggy Shubert, the piano. It brings back memories of piano and ballet lessons where I received the same criticism... if only you could learn to count! I CAN count and I could then, too! However, I remember how fun it was to just play without thinking/counting, dance without memorizing steps... it felt like flying! When I see Shubert, I remember how I could lose myself and my stress in the music and think I should start playing again... but every time I sit down with Shubert, he laughs at me. His former owner, my landlady, left him several humid summers with no air conditioner, no dehumidifier and his sound-board got wet. Now, even after tuning, it is only a matter of weeks before the pegs loosen and... well you can imagine. It is less like flying and more like crawling through... Anyway, instead of playing the piano, I go dancing at salsa clubs. Well, unfortunately, the Taiwanese way is to take lessons, memorize steps and count in my ear. I'd rather feel the music have 'sweet nothings' whispered in my ear (even if I dance badly), but whatever... at least I can leave the counting /memorizing to someone else.

Wednesday Nite, May 12 - Salsa Party at Patio - 9:00pm! A friend and I arranged to meet at Patio (in the Neo 19 building near Warner Village) at 8:00 for dinner followed by a night of dancing. Patio is across the city from my office, so I left 30 minutes before the meeting time...One taxi ride later, I arrived to find out that I had caught my shirt on something and unravelled the bottom hem. Having come straight from work, I was already looking considerably less than salsa-sexy! I ran to the nearest shop (Mango) to find a quick replacement. As Taiwan stocks only smaller sizes... and being as a few years in Taiwan (everything tastes better with a little pork fat, you know?) has increased my dress size, my options are limited. 5 minutes later and with my wallet considerably lighter, I run to Patio to see if G is there yet. She isn't. The host leads me to my table. We descend into a sunken retro pit! She shows me to my circular gray fuzzy chair with a view of the geometric white balastrades and the light patterns being projected on the ceiling. She also informs me that the live salsa band won't start until 10:00- an hour later than advertised! (On weeknights, every hour is precious)

One of Edgar Allan Poe’s most-celebrated works is “Dream-Land.” In this poem, Poe employs the term “Thulé” in the sixth and fifty-sixth lines, which Mabbott attributes to Virgil's usage. Virgil used “Thulé” to denote an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While Virgil did indeed use the term, a more contemporary influence is noteworthy. Poe was deeply interested in German literature.

This connection is significant as it reveals Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," highlights the similarities between Poe and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was probably imitating Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of the poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second upon Goethe’s death in 1832. Within the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells the story of a king who loses his wife and subsequently his will to live, mirroring a dark, drinking-addled doppelganger of Poe's own suffering.

Poe references “Thulé” twice in his collected works. In "The Pit and the Pendulum," he uses the phrase "ultma Thulé," but in "Dream-Land," he uses the term twice as bookends for the poem. “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, and haunted by dead friends, with a shaded world devoid of color—scenes that echo Goethe's poem where the king, after losing his wife, becomes isolated and loses his will to live. The entire poem appears as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s narrative.

Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known even if only through his admiration for Tennyson. Poe’s respect for Tennyson would naturally have led him to Goethe's works, given the many reproductions of Goethe's writings that were circulating after their initial publication.

Under California law, could a customer injured by slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating the store manager acted with malice? The manager was informed of the spill twice and failed to clean it for half an hour while eating dinner. A judge might not dismiss the claim right away, but the plaintiff would need to prove the manager's actions were done with conscious disregard for the potential harm and were particularly despicable. The store had seen multiple slip-and-fall incidents before, yet the manager did nothing to ensure safety. On October 13, 2009, Rich Wayne reported the spill, but the manager, Paul Martin, was on dinner break and didn't have time for "customer complaints." Later, Mary J. Haddigan reported the spill again, but Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, injuring her back. Five similar incidents had occurred in 2009. Palmer is suing for damages, and we're considering a motion to dismiss the punitive damage claim. California law allows punitive damages for actions with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The manager's actions could be considered malicious if he was aware of the risk but deliberately ignored it. So, could the manager's actions be deemed despicable enough to warrant punitive damages?

Four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC, where we frequently debated whether Islam is inherently hostile. This question feels more pertinent today than ever, especially considering the media's swing from antagonistic views post-9/11 to an extreme form of tolerance in America. In 2001, the idea of a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with a clear Muslim lineage, was unimaginable. The Prophet Muhammad's biography, as I understand it, presents a figure who contradicts the historical accounts of his actions. While historical records suggest he conquered tribes and forced them to convert to Islam, the biography portrays him as a misunderstood martyr who humbly converted people through his teachings. This narrative echoes the ministries and miracles of Jesus, with stories of multiplying food to feed multitudes, aiming to portray Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove his teachings but simply lived them. This approach diminishes the life and miracles of Jesus, effectively stealing and crediting Muhammad's attributes to Christ. The biography also relies heavily on third-party accounts, which, while purporting to validate the stories, often diminish their credibility. What bothers me most is the effort to elevate Muhammad as a godly figure, depicting him as humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, historical facts contradict this portrayal, raising questions about how Muslims today view Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus, as they were established during his lifetime, quickly became overshadowed in the evolution of Christian thought following his passing. When we examine the broader picture of Christianity's history, we observe a persistent drift away from its origins. The world today is increasingly aware and progressive, with traditionalists who resist new ideas making up a smaller and smaller part of the population. Among Christians, historical consciousness will grow significantly in the coming years. There will be a strong desire to differentiate between the doctrines that were added over time and the actual teachings of Jesus. This shift may take several decades or even centuries, but it is inevitable: Christianity will revert to its original form. A movement will emerge, peeling away layers of doctrine one by one, like rewinding time, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains. As this trend spreads across the United States and Europe, it will inspire masses to worship as if living during Jesus' time, adhering strictly to his teachings. The church will remain a strong institution guiding this process. However, as the theological clock turns backward, the current diversity within Christendom will give way to more uniformity in belief and practice. Differences between regions, denominations, and divisions will diminish, with similarities increasing. History is filled with such reversions. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian realm. Our country has evolved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. This great reversal in Christian history will occur, undoing diversity to find the source, and reducing divisions to a common faith. This process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words as metaphorical rather than literal. So, what has changed since Jesus' time? Looking back through history, we find only Judaism, the original foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was divided into various sects: Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

The Jungle, in essence, exposes the inherent greed and self-interest that lies within human nature. Individuals are driven to prioritize their own well-being above all else, rarely considering those less fortunate. The story illustrates this through the owners and managers of the immense factories, their only concern being the growth and prosperity of their businesses. They disregard any obstacles or collateral damage, indicated by Sinclair's vivid description: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." The factory owners show no regard for the environmental impact or the plight of those affected by the pollution. They also disregard their employees' welfare, pushing them to work grueling hours to maximize profits, as Sinclair puts it, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." With little to no worker protection laws or regulations, managers and owners exploit their employees, often laying off vast numbers without notice or compensation. The workers, trapped in this system, are likened to slaves, enduring horrendous conditions both in and out of the factories. The lack of aid or information for these workers, coupled with ineffective unions, leaves them at the mercy of their oppressors.

Many writers employ various strategies to evoke certain emotions or attitudes about significant topics. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs several of these techniques in his novel "The Great Gatsby." Sometimes, he pairs unusual adjectives with nouns to create a specific atmosphere around a topic. Other times, he assigns meaning to symbols and uses them to achieve the same goal. Fitzgerald frequently uses colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink in this manner. In "The Great Gatsby," he invests meaning into white/gray and red/pink, then employs these meanings to remind readers of feelings connected to important objects.

The associations Fitzgerald establishes with white/gray are uniformity, with white being associated with higher class and gray with aging and faded prestige. Throughout the novel, he reinforces these connections. Daisy and Jordan are often seen in white, and even Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, while Tom sports a white shirt when meeting Myrtle. The only exception is when Nick first observes Gatsby's party, where the halls are filled with vibrant primary colors. Fitzgerald further emphasizes these colors by describing mundane subjects in these hues: Nick descends "down the white chasms of lower New York," the guests at Gatsby's parties appear as "gray names" on his schedule, and Catherine's apartment is likened to "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses," all signifying uniformity. He also uses white and gray to depict ordinary people or places, such as the "white girlhood" of Daisy and Jordan, the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, and the "gray" Italian child and the "gray old man" selling dogs.

Once Fitzgerald has imbued white/gray with these meanings, he employs them to convey a sense of unimportance or uniformity. This technique begins with Daisy. After a prolonged absence, Fitzgerald describes Daisy in white, making her seem less like a character and more like a uniform, desired object for Gatsby. He reinforces this impression by describing her "gray haze of fur collar" and her white dress during Tom and Gatsby's encounter, diminishing her significance as a character.

San Diego County is a farming paradise, basking in its mild, sunny climate. Its fertile soil produces an array of crops, from tomatoes and citrus to leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The demand for organic community-supported agriculture here is robust, with many local organizations boasting lengthy waitlists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms also offer tours, hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities, allowing landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat and creating new revenue streams through tours and educational programs. This farming model could be a profitable endeavor, but it's not without its challenges. Organic farming requires more labor and management to handle pests, weeds, and soil fertilization without chemicals, and yields can be lower compared to conventional methods. Additionally, the landowner might seek financial assistance to maximize profits and improve habitat quality, as the area is home to numerous threatened and endangered species. The land in question is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. This land is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, home to more than a hundred species, many of which are endangered. The area has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers. This property was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and wood production for decades. The current landowner researched available government programs and organic farms in the area to explore potential cost-mitigating and wildlife-friendly farming opportunities.

Negotiations are deeply influenced by culture, which is both what it is and what it’s not, and what it signifies. Culture isn’t uniform, so statements like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are too broad. It’s more productive for a negotiator to understand the impact of a culture on the topic at hand and how it will affect negotiations. Approaching a foreign culture involves relating it to one’s own, which can lead to comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture may involve studying its history or recognizing its biases, rather than judging or attempting to change it. It's important to accept a culture as it is and work within its boundaries, especially when one has a weaker bargaining position or is on "away" territory. Respect for traditions and beliefs can help overcome cultural barriers and advance negotiations.

Culture isn't just about national or international differences. Many companies within a nation have their own corporate cultures, which can include long or flexible hours, direct or indirect communication styles, and diverse hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy, while others limit it. Looking at differences among American companies can illustrate the range of corporate cultures. Even cultures that seem uniform may conceal deeper differences.

Values are crucial to understand because they give context to a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is valued, a negotiator won’t publicly shame their company or superior. Similarly, someone from a culture that values a hard-driven bargain won't settle early. Before heading to the negotiation table, it's essential to consider these cultural values. Additionally, learning about the personal aspects of the opposing negotiator can enhance the effectiveness of the negotiation.

“The fool has said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This sentiment appears first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is the starting point for St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. Likewise, Thomas Aquinas shares this belief. Both authors are defending the same concept, so for the sake of brevity, let's assume they are both right about the God of the Bible. To fairly compare their arguments, we must presume the existence of the God they believe in, as their arguments are aimed at proving this specific deity. However, neither provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To clarify this, we'll first look at St. Anselm’s basic argument. He suggests gaining understanding through faith, searching within ourselves for proof of God. He claims that since God exists in our understanding, we can't conceive of his non-existence. While his explanation can be convoluted, the core idea is that God's existence is found within our own minds. He implies that no external evidence is needed. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts.

Thomas Aquinas, however, believes in proving God's existence through reason and empirical evidence, without any need for faith. This approach could aid in evangelism by persuading people with logic. Aquinas presents five logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each, he shows that the proof of God lies in logical necessity. If you know you're missing one puzzle piece, you can infer its existence and features without seeing it.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince named Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned worldly affairs and attained enlightenment, founding Buddhism, which is now the most traditional sect known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion has been around for roughly 2,500 years and has evolved quite a bit since Buddha's time. For example, in the Theravada country of Sri Lanka, they celebrate an annual water-cutting ceremony. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ritual, which holds spiritual significance despite Buddha never teaching about such a ceremony. These transformations are evident across the board, from superficial customs to the religion's core beliefs. The Theravada community, whether from the monastic or lay perspective, has had to adapt its doctrines over time due to both internal and external influences, both hostile and benign.

There are several key terms we'll use throughout this discussion: internal versus external forces. An internal force is any influence from Buddhists, regardless of their monastic status. An external force is any influence from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, while benign forces are those that do not wish to harm or help the community, although they might do so inadvertently. These terms will be used frequently.

To understand Theravada Buddhism, it's important to explore its core principles. Buddhists find refuge in the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka, or the Three Baskets, of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism, such as Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of everything). Recognizing these concepts allows one to escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which leads to the end of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) upon enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for laypeople and monks alike. Laypeople must adhere to five precepts: I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances. Monks have many more rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrine is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a path to end suffering.

America and Mexico, once locked in a heated rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893, provide a classic example of such disputes. The pinnacle of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where America emerged victorious, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. Numerous skirmishes occurred between the two nations, with tensions finally easing before the First World War. This rivalry was fueled by disagreements on religion, culture, tradition, and material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

Fifteen years ago, I was unexpectedly debilitated by a hidden illness. I was a nurse, having chosen this career to ensure a secure future, as I'd heard, "people will always get sick" from my adolescence onwards. My dream was to be a scientist or journalist, but nursing promised stability.

Now, at 46 and single, I'm disabled, relying on Social Security Disability after 15 years, with nothing left to call my own. Daily life is a struggle, and my sense of security is constantly threatened. I couldn't have survived without my family and a few friends' support. Disasters come in all sizes, and no matter how well you prepare, some are too daunting to face alone.

I concur that Americans should stop depending solely on big government. Instead, let's foster trust and mutual aid, helping each other and seeking assistance when needed. Our forefathers' resilience came from compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources, not rugged individualism.

So yes, be ready. I have emergency supplies, including a first aid kit, water purifiers, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned goods. If you have the means, start a small farm and preserve your own food. But also, get to know your neighbors.

The question arises: why do organisms evolve as they do, and are there any constraints that guide the direction of evolutionary change? While in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson suggested that even the simplest organic forms are yet to be defined mathematically, the same holds true today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both through ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study aims to explore how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help us understand the mechanisms driving the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. Using X-radiographic images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters that we entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995) to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to gain a better understanding of macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be visualized as a temporal tube that winds through 360 degrees of space. These turns or coils are known as whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis, the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl, called the body whorl, is the last one. The spire consists of all whorls except the last, with the apex being the tip and the base being the opposite end. The animal exits the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different directions: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first, view the shell from the apical perspective and determine where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts, and count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. You can trace the path of the aperture using the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture and the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, parameters can be varied to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have been relatively stagnant over the past decade. Despite making significant strides in achieving the Millennium Development Goals like water and sanitation, the progress in child and maternal health remains insufficient. This highlights a need to bolster the overall health system rather than focusing solely on targeted interventions.

While Indonesia has increased the proportion of births attended by skilled health workers to 72%, this category still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions for complicated pregnancies. As such, the maternal death rate due to hemorrhage remains high. Additionally, the percentage of children under five receiving treatment for diarrheal diseases by a health professional has declined, and postnatal care data indicates this is a concern.

Cesarean-section rates are lower than expected at around 4%, with significant disparities between urban (7%) and rural (2%) areas. This disparity underscores the inequitable access to healthcare services, which are predominantly centered in urban areas. Moreover, there is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, indicating that the poor struggle to access healthcare services due to affordability issues.

In addressing the improvements needed for neonatal and maternal care, the key question is how best to tackle the lack of healthcare services. Should Indonesia focus on programmatic interventions or strengthen the entire health system, including pre- and post-pregnancy care? While program-specific approaches can offer manageable, targeted objectives and quicker results, they often come with drawbacks. Investing heavily in one area can divert funding and human resources from other sectors, leading to duplication of services and increased paperwork.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous attention to detail and its focus on the aristocracy. Two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels diverge from the typical Victorian style by incorporating elements of mystery and the bizarre, which enriches the characters and deepens our understanding of their motivations and emotions.

“A storm of bewildering and confusing thoughts assailed his mind. He seemed to be walking with Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing heatedly. The very words they spoke echoed in his ears, and when he tried to focus on his surroundings, he found himself conversing with them. Suddenly, he started at the sound of gunshots. A cacophony of shouts and sounds filled the air, and he felt himself being hurriedly carried away by an unseen force. Through these vivid visions, there was an underlying sensation of pain that gnawed at him constantly.” (Dickens, 220)

Both works employ this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and purpose vary. In Oliver Twist, these dreams often uncover Oliver's inner turmoil, his awareness of his surroundings, and the things that pain him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he re-experiences the event in a dreamlike state, struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events unfolding around him, as well as his dire situation, evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelm him, his senses numbed, as if he’s removed from the shock of pain, feeling constant fear rather than surprise. The question arises: whose will, then, brought about his misfortune, as it certainly wasn't his own? This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control and can't even attempt to influence an event's outcome, even as his life hangs in the balance. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, as if old Fagin has begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, and influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, one could assume that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed – a day it was not, for it was gone as soon as it came, and night returned, long and yet short. Long in its dreadful silence and brief in its fleeting hours.”

A couple of years ago, I was involved in an after-school program where I tutored elementary-aged students in various subjects. While I excelled in English and reading, I was particularly drawn to helping a young boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. Initially, I couldn't understand why he had peculiar problems with certain letters, some he pronounced perfectly while others were off the mark. Intriguing, he was Latino and spoke perfect English, but his reading comprehension was a challenge. I struggled with him until one day his mother arrived. She didn't speak English, only Spanish, and with my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate. That's when it dawned on me: Adrian could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet very well. This revelation shed light on the language barrier issue in schools, especially in California. It's not always as obvious as we think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can be a significant hurdle. We need to address this problem by combining various approaches. In Adrian's case, tutoring in English reading and the alphabet was key, but for those barely speaking English, the solution is more complex.

The dual language system is a great idea, beneficial for students whose first language is Spanish and for all children. Studies show that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. However, many fear that it's a waste of resources and that the majority won't benefit. This is not true. If we made it the norm rather than the exception, all children would thrive. To achieve this, we don't need all teachers to be bilingual, but we could have bilingual aids or tutors to support the students.

From our earliest days, we're often told there exists a realm larger than us, beyond what we can grasp. Some dive into Sunday school, temples, or self-discovery, embracing their parents' faiths, while others reject them, denying any existence beyond our personal world. We may adopt beliefs, only to shift our views, each journey defining our unique spiritual selves. We seek a light to guide us from darkness into the sun.

“A cardinal,” my father said, when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, rain pounding on the tin roof, a cigarette in each hand. The gutters poured water, drowning the plants around us. He gazed into the rain, a look that was half search, half reminisce. He'd grown frail, his clothes loose, hair sparse. I felt alone, afraid, unable to discuss my sadness. I hugged him, then sat closer, lost in the rain's dance with the twilight.

My father passed in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemotherapy and radiation prolonged his agony, but not his life. I couldn't bear to watch him depart. My memories of him were of his living, not his dying. I wasn't there. I hid in my bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called.

The quintessential "Gothic Novel," in both its essence and title, is an "oxymoron of 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt elucidates in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both scorned and celebrated, accused of lacking depth yet praised for its 'terrible sublime' quality (Burke). The inaugural "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, blended "ancient" and "modern" romance tropes to birth the proto-Gothic genre and a novelistic method. Walpole employed "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to craft his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre drew from many medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even during the publication of The Castle of Otranto, the term "gothic" encompassed a variety of peoples, styles, and epochs, perceived as archaic or unsophisticated against the backdrop of "modern" societal and literary "progress." The fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new, reader-focused format ensured the Gothic's longevity, transforming it into both an obsolete and fresh experience for readers displaced in time from the original writing.

One dominant theme in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval ideal of chivalry, training a proper knight, is both preserved and reimagined in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is crucial to Gothic writers, who saw it embodying the quintessential brave, honorable, and competent knight, and who perceived a lack of these qualities in contemporary society. Through chivalric elements and manners, the "gothic past" is romanticized and idealized (anticipating the evolution to Romanticism), serving as a means to improve the present. When writing The Castle of Otranto, Walpole was immersed in political turmoil and despairing of the future, possibly attributing the supposed moral integrity and "goodness" of the gothic era to a perceived loss in contemporary society. This is evident in characters like Frederic. Before meeting him, he embodies traditional chivalric traits, described as: The description includes numerous chivalric images; Frederic is a prince, has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy, and is presumed dead by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the sequence of processes that move products from the point of customer order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The concept was introduced in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a management consultant. He described it as the process of planning, executing, and controlling all activities within the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently. Key components of supply chain management include production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these components to ensure they provide top-notch customer service.

Production is the first critical step in the supply chain. It sets the foundation for the entire process. At this stage, managers determine when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. To understand what customers want, managers can analyze the market, which is the primary indicator of customer demand. Once the demand is understood, managers can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. After these decisions, they choose the best location for production, considering volume, quality, and customer satisfaction. The next focus is on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Proper planning at this stage is essential to avoid significant delays and expenses in the long run. For instance, I've worked at Wal-Mart and Target, where thorough processes for every aspect of the business ensure smooth operations. A well-designed process layout, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, minimizes confusion and maximizes efficiency.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to determine the core capabilities of a facility and to establish outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple divisions for producing a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must choose the best division for each production process. They may also decide to outsource some work to other companies to achieve velocity, which is providing quality and flexibility while reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

The sign reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma." Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, a piece of cardboard held above her head, the chilling message scrawled in Sharpie. Burma, known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a ruthless military junta who seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, a series of protests, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution" for the color of the monks' robes, took place. Initially peaceful, they escalated into violent clashes between the monks and the military regime. Foreign journalists were imprisoned, and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed for documenting the protests. The official death toll is disputed, with Colonel Hla Win estimating thousands killed.

This is hardly new. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain total control over their citizens. Early Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors were believed to be gods, and even our current president, George W. Bush, consults weekly with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subgroup of the Republican Party.

Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where students and activists were met with a bloody crackdown, with death tolls ranging from 200 to 3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s saw Hutu militias, backed by the government, systematically slaughtering Tutsis and political moderates. And let's not forget Hitler's 'Third Reich', a regime that persecuted and killed anyone of Jewish descent.

Duke Ellington's enduring impact on jazz can be attributed to his remarkable longevity and the creative prowess he brought to his orchestra. As a pianist, his presence is often subtle in many of the compositions, but as a composer, he was exceptional at crafting rich and intricate pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. Ellington designed frameworks that allowed soloists to freely improvise, while also writing tightly orchestrated arrangements that showcased the unique styles of his musicians. This not only emphasized the tone of the entire orchestra but also allowed original sounds to emerge from the collective. Ellington's ability to harness the individual sounds of his players and their collective harmony resulted in some of the most innovative and brilliant jazz pieces ever composed.

In the Grove Music dictionary, the text discusses Ellington's unique sound and innovation, referring to 'Creole Love Call' as an early example of his use of voice as a jazz instrument. This piece, with its six choruses, demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the styles of his soloists throughout his career. In 'Creole Love Call,' the voice is used to add texture and color without lyrics, and the piece features a call and response between voice and reeds, with soloists taking turns on various instruments. The piece culminates in a climactic chorus that showcases the 'growl' technique on the voice, followed by a brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending. Ellington's use of voice in this way is a stylistic trait that permeates much of his work.

In 'Hot and Bothered,' recorded a year later, Ellington's mastery of orchestration is evident. A call and response between 'Bubber' Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing combines the vocal elements of Miley's playing with the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice, creating a rich and complementary sound. In 'It Don't Mean a Thing,' Ellington uses 'Tricky Sam' Nanton's muted trombone to great effect, introducing the melody in a way that highlights his unique style.

Ever since she was 14, she had felt a persistent longing for something, yet it remained unfulfilled. At 17, she realized her desire was someone, not something, but no one could capture her interest. Boys were attracted to her, but no one sparked her curiosity. This enigma puzzled her, and years of self-questioning yielded theories but no satisfying answers. She carried on with her life, her curiosity piqued.

A typical day at home was serene. Her parents were calm, seldom arguing, and their daughter was a lively blend of their serenity and her own exuberance, making her well-liked. Yet, today was anything but calm. As she wandered through the house seeking inspiration, she heard a cry from the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground, gasping "Ow." Panicked, she rushed to her side. "Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother, in pain, asked her to take her to the hospital. "Where should I pick you up?" she asked, guiding her hands. Strengthened by her classes, she carried her mother to the car and drove.

The hospital's sterile scent and her mother's pain filled her with fear, but she focused on helping. Carrying her mother in, she called for help, and doctors arrived to examine her. Her mother had fallen from a stool, attempting to reach a vase. She was left to sit, worried, as her mother was taken away.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as indicated by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as decreased stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a tweaked version of the Med diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, along with more monounsaturated fats compared to saturated fats, and lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. It also permits moderate alcohol consumption.

Previous studies had found an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Moreover, an intervention trial revealed that the Med diet outperformed a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. However, these studies did not delve into stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 states. Over six follow-ups from 1984 to 2004, an aMed diet score was computed from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) assessing nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses stayed in the study over the 20-year period. FFQs were validated, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical, hospital, or death records.

Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use were calculated for each FFQ. Beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed. Cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were computed to lessen random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake. Adjustments were made for potential confounders like age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and CHD and stroke risk, separately for fatal and nonfatal cases.

The findings indicated that higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular deaths (from CHD and strokes combined) were recorded. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America was hit by a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market tumbled, and many of America’s most significant and influential corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, so it’s essential to examine how it happened and how we can prevent it from recurring. In essence, the financial crisis was sparked by self-centered and naïve political decisions that pushed banks and firms to lend to sub-prime borrowers, flooding an already shaky financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and bundle these mortgages into complex securities (CDOs and CDS), which failed to withstand the subsequent defaults, spreading economic chaos.

The roots of this crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton administration. President Clinton aimed to secure his second term by boosting his popularity, prompting the administration to loosen lending restrictions. This paved the way for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, America's largest home mortgage underwriter, faced mounting pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans for low and moderate-income individuals, but also from shareholders to maintain its impressive profit growth.” Holmes warned, “However, the government-backed corporation could face difficulties in an economic downturn, potentially requiring a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan crisis in the 1980s.” As foreseen, this ill-advised lending led to economic collapse.

A multitude of factors contributed to the economic downturn, including the introduction of complex mortgage structures like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs). These instruments intertwined various sectors of the economy with the housing market, leading to excessive leverage and vulnerability to price fluctuations. The housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions, which had invested heavily in these mortgage-backed securities, facing severe financial distress. The top five U.S. investment banks reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the U.S. GDP. As a result, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become regulated commercial banks. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That's the part of your story where you spread your writing wings and take flight, enthralling readers with your spellbinding prose. Or the bit where your audience falls asleep or hits the "Back" button, cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she stumbles upon Too Much Information, and not even the good kind.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still finds herself stuck in endless stretches of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is that little demon on your shoulder whispering that you should get the background info out of the way to reach the good stuff (not to be confused with the demon urging you to share every mundane detail of your characters' lives).

Exposition means informing your audience about what happened, often in plain language. In movies, exposition occurs when one character shares a lengthy info dump with another, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author does the explaining.

Consider this: As you read a story, you're told the heroine met her love at a specific place and time, they were wed in a grand ceremony, and her husband was killed right before her eyes. You'd expect this sequence to be engaging, with the author spending time on the husband's character, demonstrating through his words and actions how deeply he loves his wife. Similarly, you'd expect the heroine to reveal how his presence enriched her life, especially if the story later states that her life changed for the better because of him. A good introduction to the husband's character would make you care about his fate and provide insights into the heroine's persona: what she saw in him, the depth of their connection, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams reflected through his eyes, and more. You'd mourn his death with her and grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In essence, you'd expect more than a basic recap: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you must provide that depth. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, presses on*) Sometimes, it's tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character who used to serve in the Air Force, now manages a gas station at night, was married twice, has no kids, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I tuned in to two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. First was NBC 4's live morning show on August 13, 2011. The top story featured a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. The name of the victim was not mentioned, but his mugshot was shown, depicting what seemed like someone pure evil. They only dedicated about two minutes to this story as it was unfolding. They provided minimal details, simply stating he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I believe they gave this story the right amount of attention.

The second story was about an early morning shooting of 18-year-old Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and there were no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was investigating. This story seemed rushed, and I believe that might be due to the fact that the victim was a minority. I've noticed this before: when a crime involves a minority victim, the media often dedicates less time to it. If a white person is kidnapped or harmed, the media goes into overdrive, but minority victims often barely get a mention.

Next, they covered a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about the location, and it was determined to be a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers were offering a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They mentioned temperatures would stay in the mid to low eighties for the weekend, but the length of time dedicated to this story was relatively short. They intended to use it as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt, about six feet tall and 150 pounds. They seemed to focus unusually on his race and skin color. Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin sentenced to distribute marijuana from Texas to Ohio. Instead of stating his sentence as 25 years, they said "300 months," and they mentioned he was Hispanic, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

There is an unbreakable bond between brothers, forged in the fires of shared blood and bound by emotions few understand. Among these feelings are love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers hold each other up as no one else can, seeing in one another their own reflection. This bond is sturdiest in the darkest times, when emotions rise to the surface, good or ill. When a brother looks into his sibling’s eyes, he sees not just a reflection, but his true self laid bare. It is in their actions and the consequences that follow that their true character is revealed. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers navigate the complexities of this bond, with all its emotions. Set against a lush, vivid backdrop, these boys venture on a futile journey, where bitterness and pride clash, and only one survives. This theme is explored through the protagonist, Doodle, and his interactions with his older brother, as well as through the narrator’s perspective, which paints a picture of Doodle’s complex feelings and the influence they have on his actions.

The core of Doodle’s actions is pride, from their first outing to their final, fateful adventure. He had envisioned a brother to teach, to adventure with, to race with, but Doodle’s weak heart and frail condition dashed those dreams. Doodle was a constant reminder of the protagonist’s unfulfilled aspirations. Faced with this reality, the protagonist felt resentment and even considered harming Doodle. Yet, a simple smile from his brother could melt his heart, showing his love for Doodle was stronger than his frustrations. This is the struggle of the bond, where love and hate intertwine, understood only by those who share it.

The human brain is a complex, imaginative information-processing system. Its metaphors have evolved alongside technology, transitioning from being likened to a wax tablet, then to a scroll of papyrus, a book, and finally, a computer. As you delve into brain science, remember that these metaphors have their limitations and can mislead. Information processing commences with sensory organs transforming physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. The brain's algorithms repeatedly reconfigure this sensory data through bottom-up and top-down processing.

For instance, when you gaze at a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing compiles basic information like color, orientation, and object borders to identify the box. Meanwhile, top-down processing hastens recognition by leveraging decisions from preceding bottom-up stages, such as determining the object as a black box rather than a hole. The brain's attention filter then assesses the signal's significance, determining which cognitive processes should engage.

Information processing is cyclical, with attention modulating results repeatedly. For the brain to process information, storage is necessary, encompassing various memory types: sensory, working, and long-term. Encoding varies by sensory stimuli; for example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, phonemically, or semantically. Once stored, information needs maintenance; working memory, which retains data for about 20 seconds, might be maintained by electrical signals looping through specific neurons. Long-term memory's maintenance is hypothesized to involve protein structures.

Brain knowledge organization models range from human memory retrieval to computer science and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits nodes representing concepts interlinked based on relatedness, like "chair" linked to "table" and "wooden."

Aldous Huxley, in his dystopian novel Brave New World, warns of the impending dangers of both technology and the capitalist system that perpetuates it. In this society, individuality is suppressed, and people are conditioned from birth to prioritize immediate happiness. The populace is manipulated by the World Controller, who enforces a singular ideology. Through the lens of Marxist theory, one can see Huxley's critique of developing economic systems. Key Marxist terms like homogeny and reification highlight the flaws in the capitalist structure of his time.

Huxley satirizes capitalism by employing the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Citizens are kept ignorant of their true economic relations, focused solely on personal gain. This is achieved through the conditioning of the population, evident in the emphasis on hypnopædia which reinforces the desire to consume and indulge. The World Controller controls this manipulation, with the lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, being entirely unaware of their own exploitation. The upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, also accept their roles, with few exceptions like Bernard. The interactions between social classes demonstrate the oppression inherent in capitalism.

Emotional depth and genuine relationships are absent in Brave New World. Characters lack personal growth, and interactions are superficial, with discussions focusing on physical appearance and sexual encounters. The societal classes' complacency with their roles underscores the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their obedience to their place in the hierarchy reflects Marxist theories about the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume and comply.

I've been studying at University Park for about two and a half years, which equates to four and a half semesters. Navigating campus can be a challenge, especially for freshmen like me who were placed in East Halls, the farthest dorms from the center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in the Willard building, for instance, could take up to 25 minutes, and that's without the bad weather that's common here. An alumni I spoke to mentioned that East Halls used to be separated from the rest of the campus by large patches of unused land. Today, that space is filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and apartments, making the campus larger and harder to get around. So, what's the solution to this mobility issue? In my opinion, it's cycling, but it's not just about having a bike; the campus needs to be designed with cyclists in mind.

I recently discussed this with a friend who had stopped cycling for several years. He said, "Bikes are great. They're the only way to get around." Cycling is not only healthy but also efficient. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exercise can take you 30 miles or more. As a student living off campus, I've found the most intelligent decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. My daily commute to Thomas building is a simple 5-minute ride compared to a 25-minute walk. The only downside is Pollock Road, the direct route from my house to Thomas, which isn't always the easiest to traverse. While walking has its merits, I'm too busy to walk. Without a bike, walking would be my only reliable option for class, adding 30-40 minutes to my daily commute. That's over two and a half hours every week, not to mention the time I'd spend walking to other classes and appointments. That's time I simply can't afford to spare.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music.
